AbortMultipartUpload.name: AbortMultipartUpload
AbortMultipartUpload.documentation:
Aborts a multipart upload.

To verify that all parts have been removed, so you don't get charged for the part storage, you should call the List Parts operation and ensure the parts list is empty.

AddLegalHold.name: AddLegalHold
AddLegalHold.documentation: Add a legal hold on an object. The legal hold identifiers are stored in the object metadata along with the timestamp of when they are POSTed to the object. The presence of any legal hold identifiers prevents the modification or deletion of the object data, even if the retention period has expired. Legal Holds can only be added to objects in a bucket with a protection policy. Otherwise a 400 error will be returned.

CompleteMultipartUpload.name: CompleteMultipartUpload
CompleteMultipartUpload.documentation: Completes a multipart upload by assembling previously uploaded parts.

CopyObject.name: CopyObject
CopyObject.documentation: Creates a copy of an object that is already stored in Amazon S3.

CreateMultipartUpload.name: CreateMultipartUpload
CreateMultipartUpload.documentation:
Initiates a multipart upload and returns an upload ID.

Note: After you initiate multipart upload and upload one or more parts, you must either complete or abort multipart upload in order to stop getting charged for storage of the uploaded parts. Only after you either complete or abort multipart upload, Amazon S3 frees up the parts storage and stops charging you for the parts storage.

DeleteBucket.name: DeleteBucket
DeleteBucket.documentation: Deletes the bucket. All objects in the bucket must be deleted before the bucket itself can be deleted.

DeleteBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.name: DeleteBucketAnalyticsConfiguration
DeleteBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.documentation: Deletes an analytics configuration for the bucket (specified by the analytics configuration ID).

DeleteBucketCors.name: DeleteBucketCors
DeleteBucketCors.documentation: Deletes the cors configuration information set for the bucket.

DeleteBucketInventoryConfiguration.name: DeleteBucketInventoryConfiguration
DeleteBucketInventoryConfiguration.documentation: Deletes an inventory configuration (identified by the inventory ID) from the bucket.

DeleteBucketLifecycle.name: DeleteBucketLifecycle
DeleteBucketLifecycle.documentation: Deletes the lifecycle configuration from the bucket.

DeleteBucketMetricsConfiguration.name: DeleteBucketMetricsConfiguration
DeleteBucketMetricsConfiguration.documentation: Deletes a metrics configuration (specified by the metrics configuration ID) from the bucket.

DeleteBucketPolicy.name: DeleteBucketPolicy
DeleteBucketPolicy.documentation: Deletes the policy from the bucket.

DeleteBucketReplication.name: DeleteBucketReplication
DeleteBucketReplication.documentation: Deletes the replication configuration from the bucket.

DeleteBucketWebsite.name: DeleteBucketWebsite
DeleteBucketWebsite.documentation: This operation removes the website configuration from the bucket.

DeleteLegalHold.name: DeleteLegalHold
DeleteLegalHold.documentation: Remove Legal hold on an object. The legal hold identifiers are stored in the object metadata along with the timestamp of when they are POSTed to the object. The presence of any legal hold identifiers prevents the modification or deletion of the object data, even if the retention period has expired.

DeleteObject.name: DeleteObject
DeleteObject.documentation: Removes an object. If the object doesn't exist, Amazon S3 does not remove any objects.

DeleteObjects.name: DeleteObjects
DeleteObjects.documentation: This operation enables you to delete multiple objects from a bucket using a single HTTP request. You may specify up to 1000 keys.

ExtendObjectRetention.name: ExtendObjectRetention
ExtendObjectRetention.documentation: This implementation of the POST operation uses the extendRetention sub-resource to extend the retention period of a protected object in a protected vault.

GetBucketAccelerateConfiguration.name: GetBucketAccelerateConfiguration
GetBucketAccelerateConfiguration.documentation: Returns the accelerate configuration of a bucket.

GetBucketAcl.name: GetBucketAcl
GetBucketAcl.documentation: Gets the access control policy for the bucket.

GetBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.name: GetBucketAnalyticsConfiguration
GetBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.documentation: Gets an analytics configuration for the bucket (specified by the analytics configuration ID).

GetBucketAspera.name: GetBucketAspera
GetBucketAspera.documentation: Gets Aspera access and secret keys for the bucket.

GetBucketCors.name: GetBucketCors
GetBucketCors.documentation: Returns the cors configuration for the bucket.

GetBucketInventoryConfiguration.name: GetBucketInventoryConfiguration
GetBucketInventoryConfiguration.documentation: Returns an inventory configuration (identified by the inventory ID) from the bucket.

GetBucketLifecycleConfiguration.name: GetBucketLifecycleConfiguration
GetBucketLifecycleConfiguration.documentation: Returns the lifecycle configuration information set on the bucket.

GetBucketLocation.name: GetBucketLocation
GetBucketLocation.documentation: Returns the region the bucket resides in.

GetBucketMetricsConfiguration.name: GetBucketMetricsConfiguration
GetBucketMetricsConfiguration.documentation: Gets a metrics configuration (specified by the metrics configuration ID) from the bucket.

GetBucketProtectionConfiguration.name: GetBucketProtectionConfiguration
GetBucketProtectionConfiguration.documentation: Returns the protection configuration of a bucket.EnablePermanentRetention flag will only be returned if the flag is set to true for a bucket.

GetBucketReplication.name: GetBucketReplication
GetBucketReplication.documentation: Returns the replication configuration of a bucket.

GetObjectAcl.name: GetObjectAcl
GetObjectAcl.documentation: Returns the access control list (ACL) of an object.

GetObjectTorrent.name: GetObjectTorrent
GetObjectTorrent.documentation: Return torrent files from a bucket.

HeadBucket.name: HeadBucket
HeadBucket.documentation: This operation is useful to determine if a bucket exists and you have permission to access it.

HeadObject.name: HeadObject
HeadObject.documentation: The HEAD operation retrieves metadata from an object without returning the object itself. This operation is useful if you're only interested in an object's metadata. To use HEAD, you must have READ access to the object.

ListBucketAnalyticsConfigurations.name: ListBucketAnalyticsConfigurations
ListBucketAnalyticsConfigurations.documentation: Lists the analytics configurations for the bucket.

ListBucketInventoryConfigurations.name: ListBucketInventoryConfigurations
ListBucketInventoryConfigurations.documentation: Returns a list of inventory configurations for the bucket.

ListBucketMetricsConfigurations.name: ListBucketMetricsConfigurations
ListBucketMetricsConfigurations.documentation: Lists the metrics configurations for the bucket.

ListBuckets.name: ListBuckets
ListBuckets.documentation: Returns a list of all buckets owned by the authenticated sender of the request.

ListLegalHolds.name: ListLegalHolds
ListLegalHolds.documentation: Returns a list of legal holds on an object

ListMultipartUploads.name: ListMultipartUploads
ListMultipartUploads.documentation: This operation lists in-progress multipart uploads.

ListObjects.name: ListObjects
ListObjects.documentation: Returns some or all (up to 1000) of the objects in a bucket. You can use the request parameters as selection criteria to return a subset of the objects in a bucket.

ListObjectsV2.name: ListObjectsV2
ListObjectsV2.documentation: Returns some or all (up to 1000) of the objects in a bucket. You can use the request parameters as selection criteria to return a subset of the objects in a bucket. Note: ListObjectsV2 is the revised List Objects API and we recommend you use this revised API for new application development.

ListParts.name: ListParts
ListParts.documentation: Lists the parts that have been uploaded for a specific multipart upload.

PutBucketAccelerateConfiguration.name: PutBucketAccelerateConfiguration
PutBucketAccelerateConfiguration.documentation: Sets the accelerate configuration of an existing bucket.

PutBucketProtectionConfiguration.name: PutBucketProtectionConfiguration
PutBucketProtectionConfiguration.documentation: Sets the protection configuration of an existing bucket. EnablePermanentRetention is optional and if not included is considered to be false. Once set to true, must be included in any subsequent PUT Bucket?protection requests for that bucket.

PutBucketAcl.name: PutBucketAcl
PutBucketAcl.documentation: Sets the permissions on a bucket using access control lists (ACL).

PutBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.name: PutBucketAnalyticsConfiguration
PutBucketAnalyticsConfiguration.documentation: Sets an analytics configuration for the bucket (specified by the analytics configuration ID).

PutBucketCors.name: PutBucketCors
PutBucketCors.documentation: Sets the cors configuration for a bucket.

PutBucketInventoryConfiguration.name: PutBucketInventoryConfiguration
PutBucketInventoryConfiguration.documentation: Adds an inventory configuration (identified by the inventory ID) from the bucket.

PutBucketLifecycleConfiguration.name: PutBucketLifecycleConfiguration
PutBucketLifecycleConfiguration.documentation: Sets lifecycle configuration for your bucket. If a lifecycle configuration exists, it replaces it.

PutBucketMetricsConfiguration.name: PutBucketMetricsConfiguration
PutBucketMetricsConfiguration.documentation: Sets a metrics configuration (specified by the metrics configuration ID) for the bucket.

PutBucketReplication.name: PutBucketReplication
PutBucketReplication.documentation: Creates a new replication configuration (or replaces an existing one, if present).

PutObject.name: PutObject
PutObject.documentation: Adds an object to a bucket.

PutObjectAcl.name: PutObjectAcl
PutObjectAcl.documentation: uses the acl subresource to set the access control list (ACL) permissions for an object that already exists in a bucket

RestoreObject.name: RestoreObject
RestoreObject.documentation: Restores an archived copy of an object back into Amazon S3

UploadPart.name: UploadPart
UploadPart.documentation:
Uploads a part in a multipart upload.

Note: After you initiate multipart upload and upload one or more parts, you must either complete or abort multipart upload in order to stop getting charged for storage of the uploaded parts. Only after you either complete or abort multipart upload, Amazon S3 frees up the parts storage and stops charging you for the parts storage.

UploadPartCopy.name: UploadPartCopy
UploadPartCopy.documentation: Uploads a part by copying data from an existing object as data source.

DaysAfterInitiation.documentation: Indicates the number of days that must pass since initiation for Lifecycle to abort an Incomplete Multipart Upload.

AbortIncompleteMultipartUpload.documentation: Specifies the days since the initiation of an Incomplete Multipart Upload that Lifecycle will wait before permanently removing all parts of the upload.

Status.documentation: The accelerate configuration of the bucket.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix to use when evaluating an AND predicate.

Id.documentation: The identifier used to represent an analytics configuration.

Filter.documentation: The filter used to describe a set of objects for analyses. A filter must have exactly one prefix, one tag, or one conjunction (AnalyticsAndOperator). If no filter is provided, all objects will be considered in any analysis.

StorageClassAnalysis.documentation: If present, it indicates that data related to access patterns will be collected and made available to analyze the tradeoffs between different storage classes.

S3BucketDestination.documentation: A destination signifying output to an S3 bucket.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix to use when evaluating an analytics filter.

Tag.documentation: The tag to use when evaluating an analytics filter.

And.documentation: A conjunction (logical AND) of predicates, which is used in evaluating an analytics filter. The operator must have at least two predicates.

Format.documentation: The file format used when exporting data to Amazon S3.

BucketAccountId.documentation: The account ID that owns the destination bucket. If no account ID is provided, the owner will not be validated prior to exporting data.

Bucket.documentation: The Amazon resource name (ARN) of the bucket to which data is exported.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix to use when exporting data. The exported data begins with this prefix.

BucketAlreadyExists.documentation: The requested bucket name is not available. The bucket namespace is shared by all users of the system. Please select a different name and try again.

AllowedHeaders.documentation: Specifies which headers are allowed in a pre-flight OPTIONS request.

AllowedMethods.documentation: Identifies HTTP methods that the domain/origin specified in the rule is allowed to execute.

AllowedOrigins.documentation: One or more origins you want customers to be able to access the bucket from.

ExposeHeaders.documentation: One or more headers in the response that you want customers to be able to access from their applications (for example, from a JavaScript XMLHttpRequest object).

MaxAgeSeconds.documentation: The time in seconds that your browser is to cache the preflight response for the specified resource.

Expiration.documentation: If the object expiration is configured, this will contain the expiration date (expiry-date) and rule ID (rule-id). The value of rule-id is URL encoded.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

RetentionExpirationDate.documentation: Date on which it will be legal to delete or modify the object. You can only specify this or the Retention-Period header. If both are specified a 400 error will be returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used.

RetentionLegalHoldId.documentation: A single legal hold to apply to the object. A legal hold is a character long string of max length 64. The object cannot be overwritten or deleted until all legal holds associated with the object are removed.

RetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period to store on the object in seconds. RetentionPeriod and RetentionExpirationDate are mutually exclusive, if neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetentionPeriod value will be used. **Indefinite retention(-1)** is a valid value. **Permanent retention(-2)**, is valid only if permanent retention is enabled for the bucket.  **0** is a valid value if the bucket's MinimumRetention period is also 0.

ETag.documentation: Entity tag returned when the part was uploaded.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number that identifies the part. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

HttpErrorCodeReturnedEquals.documentation: The HTTP error code when the redirect is applied. In the event of an error, if the error code equals this value, then the specified redirect is applied. Required when parent element Condition is specified and sibling KeyPrefixEquals is not specified. If both are specified, then both must be true for the redirect to be applied.

KeyPrefixEquals.documentation: The object key name prefix when the redirect is applied. For example, to redirect requests for ExamplePage.html, the key prefix will be ExamplePage.html. To redirect request for all pages with the prefix docs/, the key prefix will be /docs, which identifies all objects in the docs/ folder. Required when the parent element Condition is specified and sibling HttpErrorCodeReturnedEquals is not specified. If both conditions are specified, both must be true for the redirect to be applied.

Expiration.documentation: If the object expiration is configured, the response includes this header.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header confirming the encryption algorithm used.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

ContentLanguage.documentation: The language the content is in.

ContentType.documentation: A standard MIME type describing the format of the object data.

CopySource.documentation: The name of the source bucket and key name of the source object, separated by a slash (/). Must be URL-encoded.

CopySourceIfMatch.documentation: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) matches the specified tag.

CopySourceIfModifiedSince.documentation: Copies the object if it has been modified since the specified time.

CopySourceIfNoneMatch.documentation: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) is different than the specified ETag.

CopySourceIfUnmodifiedSince.documentation: Copies the object if it hasn't been modified since the specified time.

Expires.documentation: The date and time at which the object is no longer cacheable.

GrantFullControl.documentation: Gives the grantee READ, READ_ACP, and WRITE_ACP permissions on the object.

GrantRead.documentation: Allows grantee to read the object data and its metadata.

GrantReadACP.documentation: Allows grantee to read the object ACL.

GrantWriteACP.documentation: Allows grantee to write the ACL for the applicable object.

Metadata.documentation: A map of metadata to store with the object in S3.

MetadataDirective.documentation: Specifies whether the metadata is copied from the source object or replaced with metadata provided in the request.

RetentionDirective.documentation: This header controls how the Protection state of the source object is copied to the destination object.If copied, the retention period and all legal holds are copied onto the new object. The legal hold date's is set to the date of the copy.

RetentionExpirationDate.documentation: Date on which it will be legal to delete or modify the object. This field can only be specified if Retention-Directive is REPLACE. You can only specify this or the Retention-Period header. If both are specified a 400 error will be returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used.

RetentionLegalHoldId.documentation: A single legal hold to apply to the object. This field can only be specified if Retention-Directive is REPLACE. A legal hold is a character long string of max length 64. The object cannot be overwritten or deleted until all legal holds associated with the object are removed.

RetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period to store on the object in seconds. This field can only be specified if Retention-Directive is REPLACE. If this field and Retention-Expiration-Date are specified a 400 error is returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used. 0 is a legal value assuming the bucket's minimum retention period is also 0.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

StorageClass.documentation: The type of storage to use for the object. Defaults to 'STANDARD'.

WebsiteRedirectLocation.documentation: If the bucket is configured as a website, redirects requests for this object to another object in the same bucket or to an external URL. Amazon S3 stores the value of this header in the object metadata.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

CopySourceSSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use when decrypting the source object (e.g., AES256).

CopySourceSSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use to decrypt the source object. The encryption key provided in this header must be one that was used when the source object was created.

CopySourceSSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

LastModified.documentation: Date and time at which the object was uploaded.

LocationConstraint.documentation: Specifies the region where the bucket will be created. If you don't specify a region, the bucket will be created in US Standard.

ACL.documentation: The canned ACL to apply to the bucket.

GrantFullControl.documentation: Allows grantee the read, write, read ACP, and write ACP permissions on the bucket.

GrantReadACP.documentation: Allows grantee to read the bucket ACL.

GrantWrite.documentation: Allows grantee to create, overwrite, and delete any object in the bucket.

GrantWriteACP.documentation: Allows grantee to write the ACL for the applicable bucket.

IBMServiceInstanceId.documentation: The storage account who will be the owner of the bucket.

IBMSSEKPEncryptionAlgorithm.documentation: The encryption algorithm that will be used for objects stored in the newly created bucket. Defaults to 'AES256'

IBMSSEKPCustomerRootKeyCrn.documentation: Container for describing the KMS-KP Key CRN.

AbortRuleId.documentation: Id of the lifecycle rule that makes a multipart upload eligible for abort operation.

Id.documentation: The identifier used to represent an analytics configuration.

Bucket.documentation: The name of the bucket containing the metrics configuration to delete.

IsLatest.documentation: Specifies whether the object is (true) or is not (false) the latest version of an object.

LastModified.documentation: Date and time the object was last modified.

MFA.documentation: The concatenation of the authentication device's serial number, a space, and the value that is displayed on your authentication device.
The concatenation of the authentication device's serial number, a space, and the value that is displayed on your authentication device.

StorageClass.documentation: The class of storage used to store the object.

EncodingType.documentation: Requests Amazon S3 to encode the object keys in the response and specifies the encoding method to use. An object key may contain any Unicode character; however, XML 1.0 parser cannot parse some characters, such as characters with an ASCII value from 0 to 10. For characters that are not supported in XML 1.0, you can add this parameter to request that Amazon S3 encode the keys in the response.

Key.documentation: The object key name to use when a 4XX class error occurs.

Event.documentation: Bucket event for which to send notifications.

AdditionalRetentionPeriod.documentation: Additional time, in seconds, to add to the existing retention period for the object. If this field and New-Retention-Time and/or New-Retention-Expiration-Date are specified, a 400 error will be returned. If none of the Request Headers are specified, a 400 error will be returned to the user. The retention period of an object may be extended up to bucket maximum retention period from the time of the request.

ExtendRetentionFromCurrentTime.documentation: Retention Period in seconds. The Retention will be enforced from the object creation time until current time + the value in this header. This value has to be within the ranges defined for the bucket. If this field and Additional-Retention-Period and/or New-Retention-Period and/or New-Retentiion-Expiration-Date are specified, a 400 error will be returned. If none of the Request Headers are specified, a 400 error will be returned to the user. The retention period of an object may be extended up to bucket maximum retention period from the time of the request.

NewRetentionExpirationDate.documentation: A new retention date to use for the object in place of the existing retention date.  If this value is less than the existing value stored for the object, a 400 error will be returned.  If this field and Additional-Retention-Period and/or New-Retention-Period and/or Extend-Retention-From-Current-Time are specified, a 400 error will be returned. If none of the Request Headers are specified, a 400 error will be returned to the user. The retention period of an object may be extended up to bucket maximum retention period from the time of the request.

NewRetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period, in seconds, to use for the object in place of the existing retention period stored for the object.  If this value is less than the existing value stored for the object, a 400 error will be returned.  If this field and Additional-Retention-Period and/or New-Retention-Expiration-Date and/or Extend-Retention-From-Current-Time are specified, a 400 error will be returned. If none of the Request Headers are specified, a 400 error will be returned to the user. The retention period of an object may be extended up to bucket maximum retention period from the time of the request.

ExtendObjectRetentionRequest.documentation: Container for making extensions to object retention

FilterRule.documentation: Container for key value pair that defines the criteria for the filter rule.

FilterRuleList.documentation: A list of containers for key value pair that defines the criteria for the filter rule.

Metadata.documentation: A map of metadata to store with the object in S3.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number of the object being read. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000. Effectively performs a 'ranged' GET request for the part specified. Useful for downloading just a part of an object.

Tier.documentation: Glacier retrieval tier at which the restore will be processed.

Permission.documentation: Specifies the permission given to the grantee.

ID.documentation: The canonical user ID of the grantee.

IBMSSEKPEnabled.documentation: The bucket encryption enabled or not.

IBMSSEKPCrkId.documentation: CRK ID of the Bucket encryption

Expiration.documentation: If the object expiration is configured (see PUT Bucket lifecycle), the response includes this header. It includes the expiry-date and rule-id key value pairs providing object expiration information. The value of the rule-id is URL encoded.

IbmTransition.documentation: This header is only included if an object has transition metadata.  This header will indicate the transition storage class and time of transition.  If this header and the x-amz-restore header are both included, this header will indicate the time at which the object was originally archived.

IbmRestoredCopyStorageClass.documentation: This header is only included if an object has transition metadata.  This header will indicate the transition storage class and time of transition.  If this header and the x-amz-restore header are both included, this header will indicate the time at which the object was originally archived.

Restore.documentation: Provides information about object restoration operation and expiration time of the restored object copy.

LastModified.documentation: Last modified date of the object

ContentLength.documentation: Size of the body in bytes.

ETag.documentation: An ETag is an opaque identifier assigned by a web server to a specific version of a resource found at a URL

MissingMeta.documentation: This is set to the number of metadata entries not returned in x-amz-meta headers. This can happen if you create metadata using an API like SOAP that supports more flexible metadata than the REST API. For example, using SOAP, you can create metadata whose values are not legal HTTP headers.

CacheControl.documentation: Specifies caching behavior along the request/reply chain.

ContentDisposition.documentation: Specifies presentational information for the object.

ContentEncoding.documentation: Specifies what content encodings have been applied to the object and thus what decoding mechanisms must be applied to obtain the media-type referenced by the Content-Type header field.

ContentLanguage.documentation: The language the content is in.

ContentType.documentation: A standard MIME type describing the format of the object data.

Expires.documentation: The date and time at which the object is no longer cacheable.

WebsiteRedirectLocation.documentation: If the bucket is configured as a website, redirects requests for this object to another object in the same bucket or to an external URL. Amazon S3 stores the value of this header in the object metadata.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

Metadata.documentation: A map of metadata to store with the object in S3.

RetentionExpirationDate.documentation: Date on which it will be legal to delete or modify the object. You can only specify this or the Retention-Period header. If both are specified a 400 error will be returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used.

RetentionLegalHoldCount.documentation: Returns the count of legal holds on the object. If there are no legal holds, the header is not returned

RetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period to store on the object in seconds. If this field and Retention-Expiration-Date are specified a 400 error is returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used. 0 is a legal value assuming the bucket's minimum retention period is also 0.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header confirming the encryption algorithm used.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

PartsCount.documentation: The count of parts this object has.

IfMatch.documentation: Return the object only if its entity tag (ETag) is the same as the one specified, otherwise return a 412 (precondition failed).

IfModifiedSince.documentation: Return the object only if it has been modified since the specified time, otherwise return a 304 (not modified).

IfNoneMatch.documentation: Return the object only if its entity tag (ETag) is different from the one specified, otherwise return a 304 (not modified).

IfUnmodifiedSince.documentation: Return the object only if it has not been modified since the specified time, otherwise return a 412 (precondition failed).

Range.documentation: Downloads the specified range bytes of an object. For more information about the HTTP Range header, go to http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec14.html#sec14.35.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number of the object being read. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000. Effectively performs a 'ranged' HEAD request for the part specified. Useful querying about the size of the part and the number of parts in this object.

Suffix.documentation: A suffix that is appended to a request that is for a directory on the website endpoint (e.g. if the suffix is index.html and you make a request to samplebucket/images/ the data that is returned will be for the object with the key name images/index.html) The suffix must not be empty and must not include a slash character.

ID.documentation: If the principal is an AWS account, it provides the Canonical User ID. If the principal is an IAM User, it provides a user ARN value.

Destination.documentation: Contains information about where to publish the inventory results.

IsEnabled.documentation: Specifies whether the inventory is enabled or disabled.

Filter.documentation: Specifies an inventory filter. The inventory only includes objects that meet the filter's criteria.

Id.documentation: The ID used to identify the inventory configuration.

OptionalFields.documentation: Contains the optional fields that are included in the inventory results.

Schedule.documentation: Specifies the schedule for generating inventory results.

S3BucketDestination.documentation: Contains the bucket name, file format, bucket owner (optional), and prefix (optional) where inventory results are published.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix that an object must have to be included in the inventory results.

AccountId.documentation: The ID of the account that owns the destination bucket.

Bucket.documentation: The Amazon resource name (ARN) of the bucket where inventory results will be published.

Format.documentation: Specifies the output format of the inventory results.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix that is prepended to all inventory results.

Frequency.documentation: Specifies how frequently inventory results are produced.

LambdaFunctionArn.documentation: Lambda cloud function ARN that Amazon S3 can invoke when it detects events of the specified type.

LambdaFunctionConfiguration.documentation: Container for specifying the AWS Lambda notification configuration.

ID.documentation: Unique identifier for the rule. The value cannot be longer than 255 characters.

Status.documentation: If 'Enabled', the rule is currently being applied. If 'Disabled', the rule is not currently being applied.

Transitions.documentation: Currently only one Transition allowed, also Date and Days fields are mutually exclusive.

LifecycleRuleFilter.documentation: The Filter is used to identify objects that a Lifecycle Rule applies to. Currently not supported.

IsTruncated.documentation: Indicates whether the returned list of analytics configurations is complete. A value of true indicates that the list is not complete and the NextContinuationToken will be provided for a subsequent request.

ContinuationToken.documentation: The ContinuationToken that represents where this request began.

NextContinuationToken.documentation: NextContinuationToken is sent when isTruncated is true, which indicates that there are more analytics configurations to list. The next request must include this NextContinuationToken. The token is obfuscated and is not a usable value.

AnalyticsConfigurationList.documentation: The list of analytics configurations for a bucket.

Bucket.documentation: The name of the bucket from which analytics configurations are retrieved.

ContinuationToken.documentation: The ContinuationToken that represents a placeholder from where this request should begin.
If sent in the request, the marker that is used as a starting point for this inventory configuration list response.

InventoryConfigurationList.documentation: The list of inventory configurations for a bucket.

IsTruncated.documentation: Indicates whether the returned list of inventory configurations is truncated in this response. A value of true indicates that the list is truncated.

NextContinuationToken.documentation: The marker used to continue this inventory configuration listing. Use the NextContinuationToken from this response to continue the listing in a subsequent request. The continuation token is an opaque value that Amazon S3 understands.

Bucket.documentation: The name of the bucket containing the inventory configurations to retrieve.

ContinuationToken.documentation: The marker used to continue an inventory configuration listing that has been truncated. Use the NextContinuationToken from a previously truncated list response to continue the listing. The continuation token is an opaque value that Amazon S3 understands.

IsTruncated.documentation: Indicates whether the returned list of metrics configurations is complete. A value of true indicates that the list is not complete and the NextContinuationToken will be provided for a subsequent request.

ContinuationToken.documentation: The marker that is used as a starting point for this metrics configuration list response. This value is present if it was sent in the request.

NextContinuationToken.documentation: The marker used to continue a metrics configuration listing that has been truncated. Use the NextContinuationToken from a previously truncated list response to continue the listing. The continuation token is an opaque value that Amazon S3 understands.

MetricsConfigurationList.documentation: The list of metrics configurations for a bucket.

Bucket.documentation: The name of the bucket containing the metrics configurations to retrieve.

ContinuationToken.documentation: The marker that is used to continue a metrics configuration listing that has been truncated. Use the NextContinuationToken from a previously truncated list response to continue the listing. The continuation token is an opaque value that Amazon S3 understands.

Bucket.documentation: Name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

KeyMarker.documentation: The key at or after which the listing began.

UploadIdMarker.documentation: Upload ID after which listing began.

NextKeyMarker.documentation: When a list is truncated, this element specifies the value that should be used for the key-marker request parameter in a subsequent request.

Prefix.documentation: When a prefix is provided in the request, this field contains the specified prefix. The result contains only keys starting with the specified prefix.

NextUploadIdMarker.documentation: When a list is truncated, this element specifies the value that should be used for the upload-id-marker request parameter in a subsequent request.

MaxUploads.documentation: Maximum number of multipart uploads that could have been included in the response.

IsTruncated.documentation: Indicates whether the returned list of multipart uploads is truncated. A value of true indicates that the list was truncated. The list can be truncated if the number of multipart uploads exceeds the limit allowed or specified by max uploads.

EncodingType.documentation: Encoding type used by Amazon S3 to encode object keys in the response.

IBMServiceInstanceId.documentation: The owning storage account. All buckets owned by this storage account are returned.

RetentionPeriodExpirationDate.documentation: Date on which the retention period will expire.

Delimiter.documentation: Character you use to group keys.

KeyMarker.documentation: Together with upload-id-marker, this parameter specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin.

MaxUploads.documentation: Sets the maximum number of multipart uploads, from 1 to 1,000, to return in the response body. 1,000 is the maximum number of uploads that can be returned in a response.

Prefix.documentation: Lists in-progress uploads only for those keys that begin with the specified prefix.

UploadIdMarker.documentation: Together with key-marker, specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin. If key-marker is not specified, the upload-id-marker parameter is ignored.

IsTruncated.documentation: A flag that indicates whether or not Amazon S3 returned all of the results that satisfied the search criteria.

NextMarker.documentation: When response is truncated (the IsTruncated element value in the response is true), you can use the key name in this field as marker in the subsequent request to get next set of objects. Amazon S3 lists objects in alphabetical order Note: This element is returned only if you have delimiter request parameter specified. If response does not include the NextMaker and it is truncated, you can use the value of the last Key in the response as the marker in the subsequent request to get the next set of object keys.

IBMSSEKPEnabled.documentation: The bucket encryption enabled or not.

IBMSSEKPCrkId.documentation: CRK ID of the Bucket encryption

EncodingType.documentation: Encoding type used by Amazon S3 to encode object keys in the response.

Delimiter.documentation: A delimiter is a character you use to group keys.

Marker.documentation: Specifies the key to start with when listing objects in a bucket.

MaxKeys.documentation: Sets the maximum number of keys returned in the response. The response might contain fewer keys but will never contain more.

Prefix.documentation: Limits the response to keys that begin with the specified prefix.

IsTruncated.documentation: A flag that indicates whether or not Amazon S3 returned all of the results that satisfied the search criteria.

CommonPrefixes.documentation: CommonPrefixes contains all (if there are any) keys between Prefix and the next occurrence of the string specified by delimiter

EncodingType.documentation: Encoding type used by Amazon S3 to encode object keys in the response.

KeyCount.documentation: KeyCount is the number of keys returned with this request. KeyCount will always be less than equals to MaxKeys field. Say you ask for 50 keys, your result will include less than equals 50 keys

ContinuationToken.documentation: ContinuationToken indicates Amazon S3 that the list is being continued on this bucket with a token. ContinuationToken is obfuscated and is not a real key

NextContinuationToken.documentation: NextContinuationToken is sent when isTruncated is true which means there are more keys in the bucket that can be listed. The next list requests to Amazon S3 can be continued with this NextContinuationToken. NextContinuationToken is obfuscated and is not a real key

StartAfter.documentation: StartAfter is where you want Amazon S3 to start listing from. Amazon S3 starts listing after this specified key. StartAfter can be any key in the bucket

Bucket.documentation: Name of the bucket to list.

ContinuationToken.documentation: ContinuationToken indicates Amazon S3 that the list is being continued on this bucket with a token. ContinuationToken is obfuscated and is not a real key

FetchOwner.documentation: The owner field is not present in listV2 by default, if you want to return owner field with each key in the result then set the fetch owner field to true

AbortDate.documentation: Date when multipart upload will become eligible for abort operation by lifecycle.

AbortRuleId.documentation: Id of the lifecycle rule that makes a multipart upload eligible for abort operation.

Bucket.documentation: Name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

Key.documentation: Object key for which the multipart upload was initiated.

UploadId.documentation: Upload ID identifying the multipart upload whose parts are being listed.

PartNumberMarker.documentation: Part number after which listing begins.

NextPartNumberMarker.documentation: When a list is truncated, this element specifies the last part in the list, as well as the value to use for the part-number-marker request parameter in a subsequent request.

MaxParts.documentation: Maximum number of parts that were allowed in the response.

IsTruncated.documentation: Indicates whether the returned list of parts is truncated.

Initiator.documentation: Identifies who initiated the multipart upload.

StorageClass.documentation: The class of storage used to store the object.

TargetBucket.documentation: Specifies the bucket where you want Amazon S3 to store server access logs. You can have your logs delivered to any bucket that you own, including the same bucket that is being logged. You can also configure multiple buckets to deliver their logs to the same target bucket. In this case you should choose a different TargetPrefix for each source bucket so that the delivered log files can be distinguished by key.

TargetPrefix.documentation: This element lets you specify a prefix for the keys that the log files will be stored under.

Prefix.documentation: The prefix used when evaluating an AND predicate.

Id.documentation: The ID used to identify the metrics configuration.

Filter.documentation: Specifies a metrics configuration filter. The metrics configuration will only include objects that meet the filter's criteria. A filter must be a prefix, a tag, or a conjunction (MetricsAndOperator).

Prefix.documentation: The prefix used when evaluating a metrics filter.

Tag.documentation: The tag used when evaluating a metrics filter.

And.documentation: A conjunction (logical AND) of predicates, which is used in evaluating a metrics filter. The operator must have at least two predicates, and an object must match all of the predicates in order for the filter to apply.

UploadId.documentation: Upload ID that identifies the multipart upload.

Key.documentation: Key of the object for which the multipart upload was initiated.

Initiated.documentation: Date and time at which the multipart upload was initiated.

StorageClass.documentation: The class of storage used to store the object.

Initiator.documentation: Identifies who initiated the multipart upload.

NewRetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period, in seconds, to use for the object in place of the existing retention period stored for the object. If this value is less than the existing value stored for the object, a 400 error will be returned. If this field and Additional-Retention-Period and/or New-Retention-Expiration-Date are specified, a 400 error will be returned. If none of the Request Headers are specified, a 400 error will be returned.

NoSuchBucket.documentation: The specified bucket does not exist.

NoSuchKey.documentation: The specified key does not exist.

NoSuchUpload.documentation: The specified multipart upload does not exist.

NotificationConfiguration.documentation: Container for specifying the notification configuration of the bucket. If this element is empty, notifications are turned off on the bucket.

NotificationConfigurationFilter.documentation: Container for object key name filtering rules.

NotificationId.documentation: Optional unique identifier for configurations in a notification configuration. If you don't provide one, Amazon S3 will assign an ID.

StorageClass.documentation: The class of storage used to store the object.

ObjectAlreadyInActiveTierError.documentation: This operation is not allowed against this storage tier

Key.documentation: Key name of the object to delete.

ObjectNotInActiveTierError.documentation: The source object of the COPY operation is not in the active tier and is only stored in Amazon Glacier.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number identifying the part. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

LastModified.documentation: Date and time at which the part was uploaded.

ETag.documentation: Entity tag returned when the part was uploaded.

Size.documentation: Size of the uploaded part data.

MinimumRetention.documentation: Minimum retention period for an object, if a PUT of an object specifies a shorter retention period the PUT object will fail.

DefaultRetention.documentation: Default retention period for an object, if a PUT of an object does not specify a retention period this value will be converted to seconds and used.

MaximumRetention.documentation: Maximum retention period for an object, if a PUT of an object specifies a longer retention period the PUT object will fail.

EnablePermanentRetention.documentation: Enable permanent retention for an object.

Bucket.documentation: Name of the bucket for which the accelerate configuration is set.

AccelerateConfiguration.documentation: Specifies the Accelerate Configuration you want to set for the bucket.

ACL.documentation: The canned ACL to apply to the bucket.

GrantReadACP.documentation: Allows grantee to read the bucket ACL.

GrantWrite.documentation: Allows grantee to create, overwrite, and delete any object in the bucket.

ContentLanguage.documentation: The language the content is in.

ContentLength.documentation: Size of the body in bytes. This parameter is useful when the size of the body cannot be determined automatically.

ContentMD5.documentation: The base64-encoded 128-bit MD5 digest of the part data.

ContentType.documentation: A standard MIME type describing the format of the object data.

Expires.documentation: The date and time at which the object is no longer cacheable.

GrantFullControl.documentation: Gives the grantee READ, READ_ACP, and WRITE_ACP permissions on the object.

GrantRead.documentation: Allows grantee to read the object data and its metadata.

GrantReadACP.documentation: Allows grantee to read the object ACL.

GrantWriteACP.documentation: Allows grantee to write the ACL for the applicable object.

Key.documentation: Object key for which the PUT operation was initiated.

Metadata.documentation: A map of metadata to store with the object in S3.

RetentionExpirationDate.documentation: Date on which it will be legal to delete or modify the object. You can only specify this or the Retention-Period header. If both are specified a 400 error will be returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used.

RetentionLegalHoldId.documentation: A single legal hold to apply to the object. A legal hold is a character long string of max length 64. The object cannot be overwritten or deleted until all legal holds associated with the object are removed.

RetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period to store on the object in seconds. If this field and Retention-Expiration-Date are specified a 400 error is returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used. 0 is a legal value assuming the bucket's minimum retention period is also 0.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

StorageClass.documentation: The type of storage to use for the object. Defaults to 'STANDARD'.

WebsiteRedirectLocation.documentation: If the bucket is configured as a website, redirects requests for this object to another object in the same bucket or to an external URL. Amazon S3 stores the value of this header in the object metadata.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

QueueArn.documentation: Amazon SQS queue ARN to which Amazon S3 will publish a message when it detects events of specified type.

QueueConfiguration.documentation: Container for specifying an configuration when you want Amazon S3 to publish events to an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue.

HostName.documentation: The host name to use in the redirect request.

HttpRedirectCode.documentation: The HTTP redirect code to use on the response. Not required if one of the siblings is present.

Protocol.documentation: Protocol to use (http, https) when redirecting requests. The default is the protocol that is used in the original request.

ReplaceKeyPrefixWith.documentation: The object key prefix to use in the redirect request. For example, to redirect requests for all pages with prefix docs/ (objects in the docs/ folder) to documents/, you can set a condition block with KeyPrefixEquals set to docs/ and in the Redirect set ReplaceKeyPrefixWith to /documents. Not required if one of the siblings is present. Can be present only if ReplaceKeyWith is not provided.

ReplaceKeyWith.documentation: The specific object key to use in the redirect request. For example, redirect request to error.html. Not required if one of the sibling is present. Can be present only if ReplaceKeyPrefixWith is not provided.

HostName.documentation: Name of the host where requests will be redirected.

Protocol.documentation: Protocol to use (http, https) when redirecting requests. The default is the protocol that is used in the original request.

Role.documentation: Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of an IAM role for Amazon S3 to assume when replicating the objects.

Rules.documentation: Container for information about a particular replication rule. Replication configuration must have at least one rule and can contain up to 1,000 rules.

ReplicationConfiguration.documentation: Container for replication rules. You can add as many as 1,000 rules. Total replication configuration size can be up to 2 MB.

ID.documentation: Unique identifier for the rule. The value cannot be longer than 255 characters.

Prefix.documentation: Object keyname prefix identifying one or more objects to which the rule applies. Maximum prefix length can be up to 1,024 characters. Overlapping prefixes are not supported.

Status.documentation: The rule is ignored if status is not Enabled.

RequestCharged.documentation: If present, indicates that the requester was successfully charged for the request.

RequestPayer.documentation: Confirms that the requester knows that she or he will be charged for the request. Bucket owners need not specify this parameter in their requests.

Days.documentation: Lifetime of the active copy in days

GlacierJobParameters.documentation: Glacier related prameters pertaining to this job.

RetentionPeriod.documentation: Retention period to store on the object in seconds. The object can be neither overwritten nor deleted until the amount of time specified in the retention period has elapsed. If this field and Retention-Expiration-Date are specified a 400 error is returned. If neither is specified the bucket's DefaultRetention period will be used. 0 is a legal value assuming the bucket's minimum retention period is also 0.

Condition.documentation: A container for describing a condition that must be met for the specified redirect to apply. For example, 1. If request is for pages in the /docs folder, redirect to the /documents folder. 2. If request results in HTTP error 4xx, redirect request to another host where you might process the error.

Redirect.documentation: Container for redirect information. You can redirect requests to another host, to another page, or with another protocol. In the event of an error, you can can specify a different error code to return.

S3KeyFilter.documentation: Container for object key name prefix and suffix filtering rules.

DataExport.documentation: A container used to describe how data related to the storage class analysis should be exported.

OutputSchemaVersion.documentation: The version of the output schema to use when exporting data. Must be V_1.

Destination.documentation: The place to store the data for an analysis.

Permission.documentation: Logging permissions assigned to the Grantee for the bucket.

TopicArn.documentation: Amazon SNS topic ARN to which Amazon S3 will publish a message when it detects events of specified type.

TopicConfiguration.documentation: Container for specifying the configuration when you want Amazon S3 to publish events to an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic.

Event.documentation: Bucket event for which to send notifications.

Topic.documentation: Amazon SNS topic to which Amazon S3 will publish a message to report the specified events for the bucket.

Date.documentation: Indicates at what date the object is to be moved or deleted. Should be in GMT ISO 8601 Format.

Days.documentation: Indicates the lifetime, in days, of the objects that are subject to the rule. The value must be a non-zero positive integer.

StorageClass.documentation: The class of storage used to store the object.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

CopySource.documentation: The name of the source bucket and key name of the source object, separated by a slash (/). Must be URL-encoded.

CopySourceIfMatch.documentation: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) matches the specified tag.

CopySourceIfModifiedSince.documentation: Copies the object if it has been modified since the specified time.

CopySourceIfNoneMatch.documentation: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) is different than the specified ETag.

CopySourceIfUnmodifiedSince.documentation: Copies the object if it hasn't been modified since the specified time.

CopySourceRange.documentation: The range of bytes to copy from the source object. The range value must use the form bytes=first-last, where the first and last are the zero-based byte offsets to copy. For example, bytes=0-9 indicates that you want to copy the first ten bytes of the source. You can copy a range only if the source object is greater than 5 GB.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number of part being copied. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

UploadId.documentation: Upload ID identifying the multipart upload whose part is being copied.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (e.g., AES256).

SSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header. This must be the same encryption key specified in the initiate multipart upload request.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

CopySourceSSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: Specifies the algorithm to use when decrypting the source object (e.g., AES256).

CopySourceSSECustomerKey.documentation: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use to decrypt the source object. The encryption key provided in this header must be one that was used when the source object was created.

CopySourceSSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure the encryption key was transmitted without error.

ServerSideEncryption.documentation: The Server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in S3 (e.g., AES256).

ETag.documentation: Entity tag for the uploaded object.

SSECustomerAlgorithm.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header confirming the encryption algorithm used.

SSECustomerKeyMD5.documentation: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

Bucket.documentation: Name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

ContentLength.documentation: Size of the body in bytes. This parameter is useful when the size of the body cannot be determined automatically.

ContentMD5.documentation: The base64-encoded 128-bit MD5 digest of the part data.

Key.documentation: Object key for which the multipart upload was initiated.

PartNumber.documentation: Part number of part being uploaded. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

UploadId.documentation: Upload ID identifying the multipart upload whose part is being uploaded.

The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side​-encryption​-customer-algorithm header.
